 KATHMANDU, Dec 6 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Economic development must accompany Nepal's new-found peace with Maoist former rebels if the Himalayan nation wants lasting stability, the European Union said on Thursday. Nepal's aid and tourism dependent economy was expected to have grown by only 2.5 percent in financial year 2006/07, ended in July, down from 2.8 percent a year ago despite the end of the Maoist civil war that buffeted it for years. Though tourism, the mainstay of the impoverished economy, has started to revive after last year's peace deal ending a conflict that killed more than 13,000 people, post-war political issues have received precedence over the government's economic agenda. "The Nepali people need to see a tangible improvement in their lives through better delivery of basic services," Pedro Moitinho de Almeida, head of an EU delegation, told reporters at the end of a visit to Nepal. "If their desire for change goes unfulfilled this will pose a serious threat to the long-term stability of Nepal." The Maoists, who began fighting the monarchy in 1996, ended the war and joined the political mainstream as part of the pact. But the deal received a blow in September when the Maoists quit the interim government amid a row over their demand for the immediate abolition of the monarchy, a move that forced an indefinite postponement of elections expected to cap the peace process. The EU, Nepal's largest aid donor, urged the government to rescheduled the elections early, saying the delay would erode the credibility of democratic transformation and legitimisation in Nep
